<example>
  <title>How to Check Units</title>
	
	<aside>
<title>Dimensions</title>
<p>
Sometimes, the physics will use the word dimensions to refer to the class of unit for a quantity.  For example, speed can be measured in units of km/hr, m/s, or mi/hr but the base <em>dimensions</em>, represented in square brackets, are always a length [L] divided by a time [T].
</p>
</aside>

<p>
Suppose that we have derived the escape speed of a rocket from a planet of mass <m>M</m> and radius <m>R</m> (escape speed is the speed at which an object must reach to escape the gravitational pull): <m>v_{esc} = \sqrt{\frac{2GM}{R}}</m>.  As a speed, <m>v_{esc}</m> should have units like m/s (distance divided by time).
</p>

<p>
Here, <m>G</m> represents the universal gravitational constant with units <m>\frac{\text{m}^3}{\text{s}^2\text{kg}}</m>. Since there is an equal sign, this implies that the base units of either side of the equal sign must be the same. If they are not, then we have made a mistake in our derivation of the escape speed. We can perform a unit analysis to determine if we have the same base units for each side of the equal sign.
</p>

<p>
<m>\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}} \stackrel{?}{=} \sqrt{\frac{\frac{\text{m}^3}{\text{s}^2\text{kg}}\text{kg}}{\text{m}}}=\sqrt{\frac{\text{m}^2}{\text{s}^2}}=\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}} \checkmark</m>
</p>

<p>
We can see that the physical quantities under the square root indeed have base units of [L] divided by a time [T] and so our equation holds true.  Observe that we followed the sensemaking steps outlined above: we chose a strategy (checking units), determined what units we <em>should</em> get, found the units we <em>actually</em> have, and compared the two to see that they are the same!
</p>

</example>

<heuristic xml:id="sm_numbers">
	<title>Check Numbers</title>
	<statement>
		<p>For any numerical value (with units), you want to have a sense for how reasonable the value is given numerical values for other (possibly related) contexts with the same units.  You also want to know whether the number should be positive or negative (if it is a scalar) or what direction it should point (if it is a vector).</p>
	</statement>
</heuristic>

<example>
<title>How to Check Numbers</title>
<p>Consider the example from the start of this section, where you measured the length of an object in a physics lab to be 17.4 cm.  You may want to compare this number to the length of other objects that you might expect to find in a physics lab.  For example, you might expect that many objects in a physics lab can be held in one hand; you would then want to compare the 17.4 cm measurement to the size of a human hand to evaluate its reasonableness.  The search term "human hand size" results in a measurement of between 6.8 and 7.6 inches, which you might approximate to about 7 inches<fn>when checking numbers, you do not need to be precise, just approximate</fn>.  Converting this 7 inches to SI units gives approximately 17.8 cm.  This is very close to the object you measured in the lab, so it seems like this measurement was pretty reasonable!  It is also worth noting here that length is usually given as a positive number, which this measurement is.</p>
<p>You might be asking yourself: what would an <em>unreasonable</em> answer have looked like?  Perhaps your measurement had been 174 cm instead of 17.4 cm.  This is only about ten times bigger, and still seems like a reasonable measurement for a physics lab (something about the height of a person).  On the other hand, measuring something like 17.4 km would be fairly unreasonable for an ordinary physics lab: 100,000 times bigger than a person's hand!</p>
</example>




