	<title>Units Activities</title>

			<exercise xml:id="x_identifying-units">
			<title>Practice Identifying Units</title>
			  <p>Below is a list of symbols we commonly use in physics to represent physical quantities.  For each symbol, indicate the units you would expect for the corresponding quantity.</p>
				<ol>
				<li><m>t</m> (time)</li>
				<li><m>d</m> (distance)</li>
				<li><m>m</m> (mass)</li>
				<li><m>t_f</m> (final time)</li>
				<li><m>\vec{r}</m> (position)</li>
				<li><m>A</m> (area)</li>
				</ol>
			</exercise>
			
			<exercise>
			<title>Practice Checking Units</title>
			<statement>
			  <p>Your friend has developed a new engine that creates carbon dioxide gas.  Your friend shows you an equation they created relating the volume of gas created (<m>V</m>) to the width of the engine (<m>w</m>), the amount of time the engine has been running (<m>\Delta t</m>), and the mass of a single molecule of carbon dioxide (<m>M</m>): <m>V = k\frac{w^2\Delta t}{M}</m>.  Use what you know about the other symbols in the problem to determine the units of <m>k</m>.</p>
				</statement>
				<answer>
				<p><m>\frac{\text{mkg}}{\text{s}}</m></p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
			<exercise>
			<title>Practice Identifying an Error with Units</title>
			  <p>While looking through a mathematics textbook, you come across the following equation for the surface area of a cylinder: <m>A = 2\pi rh^2 + 2\pi r^2</m>.  You suspect this equation must have a mistake in it.  How can you use units to tell what the mistake is?  How could you use units to <em>fix</em> the mistake?</p>
			</exercise>
			
		</exercises>
		
